<div id="review_1925010768" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1925010768" />
    <a title="Maninee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3725164-maninee"><img alt="Maninee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620450885p2/3725164.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1925010768?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maninee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maninee" href="/user/show/3725164-maninee">Maninee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780143066569" href="/book/show/13184358-the-shadow-lines">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3725164-maninee?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1925010768" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15849280630011571221">Yet another book which I think ought to be made mandatory reading at the school level, especially now when so many seem to think that nationalism and nationality are black and white ideas, too rigid to accommodate blurred lines or gray areas. As an added bonus, we might finally teach students from a fairly early stage to see how history is always an act of selective forgetting and that how importance is given to events in history is largely determined by <i>who</i> is retelling history and to <i>whom</i>. Per</span>
  <span id="freeText15849280630011571221" style="display:none">Yet another book which I think ought to be made mandatory reading at the school level, especially now when so many seem to think that nationalism and nationality are black and white ideas, too rigid to accommodate blurred lines or gray areas. As an added bonus, we might finally teach students from a fairly early stage to see how history is always an act of selective forgetting and that how importance is given to events in history is largely determined by <i>who</i> is retelling history and to <i>whom</i>. Perhaps the most eye-opening aspect of this book is that it neatly shows how some events which are incredibly important parts of our story as communities- can be unwittingly sidelined in our collective memories. <br /><br />Regarding nationality and national identities, Ghosh has something quite simple and elegant to say: that the borders that separate us often become mirrors because, despite the collective efforts of society to alienate us from those on the other side of the 'wall', we are more similar than we may have ever imagined possible.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15849280630011571221" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


