    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_75264876" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/75264876" />
    <a title="Ellen Pierson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1243082-ellen-pierson"><img alt="Ellen Pierson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1218486408p2/1243082.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/75264876?book_show_action=true">Oct 21, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ellen Pierson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ellen Pierson" href="/user/show/1243082-ellen-pierson">Ellen Pierson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer75264876" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4736660856775459059">this book wasn&apos;t bad, it was just that to me it read more like a draft than a finished novel. amitav ghosh is clearly a gifted writer and the book read beautifully at times, but his narrative voice and the presentation of themes could have been stronger. the expanse of time and distance within the brief novel would have been manageable if it had been handled a little bit more adeptly, but often the year and location of the action would change rather abruptly leaving you confused for a few pages </span>
  <span id="freeText4736660856775459059" style="display:none">this book wasn't bad, it was just that to me it read more like a draft than a finished novel. amitav ghosh is clearly a gifted writer and the book read beautifully at times, but his narrative voice and the presentation of themes could have been stronger. the expanse of time and distance within the brief novel would have been manageable if it had been handled a little bit more adeptly, but often the year and location of the action would change rather abruptly leaving you confused for a few pages about what was going on. additionally ghosh beats us over the head repeatedly throughout the book with the themes of imagined nationalism and the absurdity of borders. while i hardly disagree, it was just a little too easy to read benedict anderson between the lines. he also worked with the idea of violence as unspeakable, which for me would have worked a little bit better if he had evoked it rather than saying point-blank, "I can only describe second hand the manner of xx's death. I do not have the words to give it meaning" (223). babsi sidwa uses the same theme in cracking india, for example, but in that novel it is clear that the child narrator does not understand the horrific events that accompanied partition, leading the reader to wonder how anyone could. it is not necessary to spell out the theme exactly, you have to give the reader a little bit of credit. The character of May also ends up seeming like a little bit of a caricature. i can appreciate an exploration of white liberal social guilt, but sleeping on the floor every night and starving oneself just for the heck of it? come on. i think she is supposed to be kind of ridiculous but it just goes a little too far for me to even take it seriously. <br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="4736660856775459059" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


